s, and political party workers as they tried to expand democratic space in the last decade of Suharto's rule. This book is an important study not only for readers interested in contemporary Indonesia and political change in Asia, but also for all those interested in democratization processes elsewhere in the world. Unlike most other books on Indonesia, and unlike many books on democratization, it provides an account from the perspective of those who were struggling to bring about change.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aOpposition (Political science)zIndonesiaxHistoryy20th century. 4aAsian Studies. 4aHistory -- Asian. 4aPolitics -- Asia. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Process / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080476731640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804767316423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780804767316/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles